00:09:49.321 --> 00:09:52.389
It's impossible to find an answer
如果不去接受那些会让我们感到有些不适应的新事物，

152
00:09:52.413 --> 00:09:55.461
without doing new things -- things that make us uncomfortable,
那些我们不熟悉的新事物，

153
00:09:55.485 --> 00:09:56.971
things we're not used to.
我们就永远找不到答案。

154
00:09:59.401 --> 00:10:02.092
A lot of you may think it's easy for me,
你们也许会认为这对我是一件简单的事，

155
00:10:02.116 --> 00:10:03.863
because I'm relatively young.
因为我相对比较年轻。

156
00:10:04.501 --> 00:10:05.981
And it used to be that way.
曾经确实是这样。

157
00:10:07.162 --> 00:10:08.322
Used to.
曾经是。

158
00:10:10.069 --> 00:10:11.935
Until last year,
直到去年，

159
00:10:11.959 --> 00:10:21.876
when I felt the weight of my age on my shoulders the first time I opened Snapchat.
当我第一次打开Snapchat（阅后即焚）时，我终于感受到了年龄的重担。

160
00:10:22.210 --> 00:10:24.869
(Laughter)
（笑声）

161
00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:28.995
(Applause)
（掌声）

162
00:10:31.405 --> 00:10:34.245
I didn't understand a thing!
我完全弄不懂这个软件！

163
00:10:35.141 --> 00:10:37.469
I found it unnecessary,
我觉得它多余、

164
00:10:37.493 --> 00:10:40.635
useless, hard to understand;
无用、晦涩难懂。

165
00:10:40.659 --> 00:10:42.547
it looked like a camera!
它看起来就是个照相机！

166
00:10:42.571 --> 00:10:44.247
It didn't have menu options!
甚至没有菜单选项！

167
00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:49.268
It was the first time I felt the gap
这是我第一次感受到代沟，

168
00:10:49.292 --> 00:10:51.884
that sometimes exists between kids and adults.
儿童与成人之间的代沟。

169
00:10:53.562 --> 00:10:56.822
But it was also an opportunity to do the right thing,
但这也是一个让我去做我应做的事情的机会：

170
00:10:56.846 --> 00:10:59.196
to leave my comfort zone, to force myself.
强迫我离开自己的心理舒适区。

171
00:11:00.768 --> 00:11:04.079
I never thought I'd ever use Snapchat,
我从不认为我会去使用 Snapchat，

172
00:11:04.103 --> 00:11:08.705
but then I asked my teenage cousin to show me how to use it.
但随后我请我十几岁的表妹教我该如何使用它。

173
00:11:10.169 --> 00:11:11.999
I also asked why she used it.
我同时也问她为什么会使用这个软件。

174
00:11:12.608 --> 00:11:14.040
What was fun about it?
它有什么有趣的？

175
00:11:15.558 --> 00:11:17.118
We had a really nice talk.
这是一次非常愉快的对话。

176
00:11:17.749 --> 00:11:20.202
She showed me her Snapchat, she told me things,
她向我展示了她的 Snapchat，还教会了我很多东西，

177
00:11:20.226 --> 00:11:22.637
we got closer, we laughed.
我们变得更亲密了，我们还一同欢笑。

178
00:11:24.769 --> 00:11:26.149
Today, I use it.
如今，我也在用。

179
00:11:26.495 --> 00:11:27.995
(Laughter)
（笑声）

180
00:11:28.608 --> 00:11:30.233
I don't know if I do it right,
我不知道我是否做对了，

181
00:11:30.257 --> 00:11:34.628
but the most important thing is that I know it and I understand it.
但更重要的是，我知道了它，并且了解了它。

182
00:11:36.226 --> 00:11:40.363
The key was to overcome the initial shock
关键在于我们要克服在最初时受到的冲击，

183
00:11:40.387 --> 00:11:42.237
and do something new.
并去尝试新事物。

184
00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:45.240
Something new.
新的事物。

185
00:11:45.264 --> 00:11:48.184
Today, we have the chance to create new conversations.
如今，我们有机会去进行新的对话。

186
00:11:49.132 --> 00:11:51.448
What's the last app you downloaded?
你最近下载了什么手机软件？

187
00:11:51.472 --> 00:11:54.332
Which social network do you use to contact your friends?
你用哪个社交软件来联系朋友？

188
00:11:54.894 --> 00:11:57.084
What kind of information do you share?
你会分享哪些信息？

189
00:11:58.379 --> 00:12:00.456
Have you ever been approached by strangers?
你是否有被陌生人主动接触过？

190
00:12:02.682 --> 00:12:05.818
Could we have these conversations between kids and adults?
成人能否与孩子们展开这类对话？

191
00:12:07.356 --> 00:12:10.039
We have to force ourselves to do it. All of us.
我们所有人都必须这么做。

192
00:12:10.063 --> 00:12:14.633
Today, lots of kids are listening to us.
如今，很多孩子都在听着我们。

193
00:12:16.527 --> 00:12:19.260
Sometimes when we go to schools to give our talks,
有时，当我们去学校演讲时，

194
00:12:19.284 --> 00:12:20.934
or through social networks,
或是在社交网络上，

195
00:12:20.958 --> 00:12:23.288
kids ask or tell us things
孩子们会问我们问题，或是告诉我们一些

196
00:12:23.312 --> 00:12:27.609
they haven't told their parents or their teachers.
他们从未和父母或是老师说过的事情。

197
00:12:27.633 --> 00:12:29.713
They tell us -- they don't even know us.
他们告诉我们这些事——而他们甚至根本不了解我们。

198
00:12:32.786 --> 00:12:38.275
Those kids need to know what the risks of being online are,
孩子们必须知道网络给他们带来的风险，

199
00:12:39.994 --> 00:12:41.500
how to take care of themselves,
以及当如何照顾自己。

200
00:12:41.524 --> 00:12:45.091
but also that, fundamentally, as with almost everything else,
并且，从根本上说，像是其他几乎所有事情一样，

201
00:12:45.115 --> 00:12:48.120
kids can learn this from any adult.
孩子可以从任何大人身上学到这些。

202
00:12:51.378 --> 00:12:55.264
Online safety needs to be a conversation topic
网络安全必须成为一个国家

203
00:12:55.288 --> 00:12:57.889
in every house and every classroom in the country.
每个家庭和学校都重视的话题。

204
00:12:59.683 --> 00:13:02.340
We did a survey this year that showed that 
我们今年的一项调查显示， 

205
00:13:02.341 --> 00:13:06.263
15 percent of schools said they knew of cases of grooming in their school.
有 15% 的学校称校内存在网络性诱拐的案例。

206
00:13:07.206 --> 00:13:08.617
And this number is growing.
并且这一数字正在增长。

207
00:13:11.650 --> 00:13:15.111
Technology changed every aspect of our life,
科技改变了生活中的方方面面，

208
00:13:15.135 --> 00:13:17.876
including the risks we face
包括我们所面对的风险，

209
00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:20.302
and how we take care of ourselves.
以及该如何照顾我们自己。

210
00:13:20.326 --> 00:13:23.696
Grooming shows us this in the most painful way:
网络性诱拐以最痛苦的方式让我们意识到这一点：

211
00:13:24.908 --> 00:13:26.357
by involving our kids.
它伤害了我们的孩子。

212
00:13:28.607 --> 00:13:30.641
Are we going to do something to avoid this?
我们是否应该付出努力去避免这类事件？

213
00:13:32.022 --> 00:13:35.461
The solution starts with something as easy as:
解决这类问题的第一步其实很简单：

214
00:13:36.239 --> 00:13:37.504
talking about it.
就是去谈论它。

215
00:13:37.528 --> 00:13:38.686
Thank you.
谢谢。

216
00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:44.449
(Applause)
（掌声）